I"<<h1 id="comparison-of-the-different-conditional-constructs">Comparison of The Different Conditional Constructs</h1>

<h1 id="use-if-statement">Use <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">if</code> Statement</h1>

<ul>
  <li>Use an if statement if:
    <ul>
      <li>It is desired to test the truthiness of an expression</li>
      <li>There is a single affirmative test</li>
      <li>There is a need to evaluate different expressions for each branch</li>
      <li>It can test expressions based on ranges of values or conditions</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h1 id="use-match-statement">Use <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">match</code> Statement</h1>

<ul>
  <li>Use a <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">match</code> statement if:
    <ul>
      <li>It is desired to compare multiple possible conditions of an expression</li>
      <li>The values belong to the same domain</li>
      <li>It can test expressions based on values only, i.e., condition cannot take ranges</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h1 id="use-if-let-statement">Use <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">if let</code> Statement</h1>
<ul>
  <li>Use an if let statement if:
    <ul>
      <li>There is a pattern in the condition and it is to be matched with the scrutinee expression</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

